var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.jl","page":"Home","text":"The package is a Julia implementation of the pomp package for R.","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Package-Features","page":"Home","text":"Implementation of POMP models\nSimulation\nParticle filter\nWorkhorses (low-level interface to basic model components)\nHelper functions\nExamples","title":"Package Features"},{"category":"section","location":"#Function-Documentation","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Function Documentation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Implementation-of-POMP-models","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Implementation of POMP models"},{"category":"section","location":"#Basic-constructor","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Basic constructor"},{"category":"section","location":"#rprocess-plugins","page":"Home","text":"","title":"rprocess plugins"},{"category":"section","location":"#Simulation","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Simulation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Particle-filter","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Particle filter"},{"category":"section","location":"#Workhorses","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Workhorses"},{"category":"section","location":"#Helper-functions","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Helper functions"},{"category":"section","location":"#Examples","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Examples"},{"category":"section","location":"#The-Gompertz-model","page":"Home","text":"View the Parus data:\n\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses, RCall\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples\nP = gompertz()\nd = melt(P)\nR\"\"\"\nsvg(\"assets/figures/gompertz1.svg\",width=7,height=4) #hide\n$d |>\n  pivot_longer(-year) |>\n  ggplot(aes(x=year,y=value))+\n  geom_line()+\n  facet_wrap(~name,scales=\"free_y\",ncol=1)+\n  labs(y=\"\")+\n  theme_bw() -> pl\nprint(pl)\ndev.off() #hide\n\"\"\"\nnothing #hide\n\n(Image: gompertz_data)\n\nView a few representative simulations:\n\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses, RCall\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples\nP = gompertz()\nQ = simulate(P;params=(r=4.5,K=210.0,σₚ=0.7,σₘ=0.1,X0=150.0),nsim=5)\nd = melt(Q,:parset,:rep)\nR\"\"\"\nsvg(\"assets/figures/gompertz2.svg\",width=7,height=5) #hide\n$d |>\n  pivot_longer(-c(year,rep,parset)) |>\n  ggplot(aes(x=year,y=value,group=rep,color=factor(rep)))+\n  geom_line()+\n  geom_point()+\n  facet_wrap(~name,scales=\"free_y\",ncol=1)+\n  labs(y=\"\",color=\"replicate\")+\n  theme_bw() -> pl\nprint(pl)\ndev.off() #hide\n\"\"\"\nnothing #hide\n\n(Image: gompertz_sims)","title":"The Gompertz model"},{"category":"section","location":"#A-simple-SIR-model","page":"Home","text":"(Image: sir diagram)","title":"A simple SIR model"},{"category":"section","location":"#The-Rosenzweig-MacArthur-model","page":"Home","text":"A sample simulation.\n\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses, RCall #hide\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples #hide\nP = rmca(σ=0.1,times=range(0,400.0,step=1.0))\nd = melt(P)\nR\"\"\"\nsvg(\"assets/figures/rmca1.svg\",width=7,height=6) #hide\n$d |>\n  pivot_longer(-time) |>\n  ggplot(aes(x=time,y=value))+\n  geom_path()+\n  facet_wrap(~name,scales=\"free_y\",ncol=1)+\n  labs(y=\"\")+\n  theme_bw() -> pl\nprint(pl)\ndev.off() #hide\n\"\"\"\nnothing #hide\n\n(Image: rmca_dynamics)\n\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses, RCall #hide\nusing PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples #hide\nP = drmca(σ=0.1,times=range(0,400.0,step=1.0))\nd = melt(P)\nR\"\"\"\nsvg(\"assets/figures/drmca1.svg\",width=7,height=6) #hide\n$d |>\n  pivot_longer(-time) |>\n  ggplot(aes(x=time,y=value))+\n  geom_path()+\n  facet_wrap(~name,scales=\"free_y\",ncol=1)+\n  labs(y=\"\")+\n  theme_bw() -> pl\nprint(pl)\ndev.off() #hide\n\"\"\"\nnothing #hide\n\n(Image: drmca_dynamics)","title":"The Rosenzweig-MacArthur model"},{"category":"section","location":"#Multivariate-Brownian-motion","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Multivariate Brownian motion"},{"category":"section","location":"#Reference","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Reference"},{"category":"section","location":"#Index","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Index"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp","page":"Home","text":"pomp is the constructor for the PompObject class.\n\npomp(\n    data;\n    t0, times, timevar,\n    params,\n    accumvars,\n    rinit, rprocess,\n    rmeasure, logdmeasure,\n    rprior, logdprior,\n    userdata\n    )\n\nArguments\n\ndata: observations. The default constructor takes a vector of NamedTuples as data. One can also supply an AbstractDataFrame.\nt0: zero time, t₀.\ntimes: observation times. If data is supplied as a DataFrame (or AbstractDataFrame), times should be a Symbol which denotes the time variable in the DfataFrame. NB: the types of times and t0 must match, or an error will be generated.\ntimevar: optional symbol.  Name of the time variable.\nparams: parameters. A NamedTuple or vector of NamedTuples.\naccumvars: a NamedTuple of state variables to be reset (usually to zero) immediately before each simulation stage.\nrinit: simulator of the latent-state distribution at t₀. This component should be a function that takes parameters and, optionally, t0, the initial time. It should return a NamedTuple of state variables.\nrprocess: simulator of the latent-state process. This component should be a plugin (see euler, onestep, and discrete_time).\nrmeasure: simulator of the measurement process. This component should be a function that takes states, parameters, and, optionally, t, the current time. It should return a NamedTuple of observable variables.\nlogdmeasure: log pdf of the measurement process. This component should be a function that takes data, states, parameters, and, optionally, t, the current time. It should return a scalar.\nrprior: simulator of the prior distribution on parameters. This component should be a function that takes parameters and returns a NamedTuple of parameters. It should return a NamedTuple of parameters.\nlogdprior: log pdf of the prior distribution on parameters. This component should be a function that takes parameters. It should return a scalar.\nuserdata: an optional NamedTuple containing elements that will be furnished to each of the basic model components.\n\n\n\n\n\nGiven an AbstractPompObject, object, pomp(object) returns the underlying concrete PompObject. Calling pomp(object; args...) returns a copy of object, modified according to the keyword arguments args....\n\n\n\n\n\npomp(object::AbstractPompObject; params=missing, accumvars=missing, rinit=missing, rprocess=missing, rmeasure=missing, logdmeasure=missing)\n\nThis form returns a modified version of object. Individual basic components can be modified or removed. The default is to leave them unchanged.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.euler","page":"Home","text":"euler(stepfun; dt)\n\nThe function stepfun should advance the state by an arbitrary time-increment. The time-increment will be chosen so that equal-sized steps of duration at most dt are taken over any desired interval.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.euler"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.discrete_time","page":"Home","text":"discrete_time(stepfun; dt = 1)\n\nThe function stepfun should advance the state by one time unit. The magnitude of the time unit is dt.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.discrete_time"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.onestep","page":"Home","text":"onestep(stepfun)\n\nThe function stepfun will be called once to advance the latent-state process over an interval of arbitrary duration.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.onestep"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.vectorfield","page":"Home","text":"vectorfield(vf, integration_alg; integrator_args...)\n\nThe function vf should return a vector containing the components of the vectorfield in the same order in which they are passed to vf.\n\nThe integration_alg argument specifies the integration algorithm to be used.  See OrdinaryDiffEq.jl for more on the choices.  The keyword arguments in integrate_args... are passed to the OrdinaryDiffEq.solve() function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.vectorfield"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate","page":"Home","text":"simulate(object; nsim = 1, params, rinit, rprocess, rmeasure, args...)\n\nSimulate the POMP. Returns an array of PompObjects. At least the rinit, rprocess, and rmeasure basic components, are needed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate_array","page":"Home","text":"simulate_array(object; nsim = 1, params, rinit, rprocess, rmeasure, args...)\n\nSimulate the POMP. At least the rinit, rprocess, and rmeasure basic components, are needed. Return an array containing the simulated sample paths.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate_array"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pfilter","page":"Home","text":"pfilter(object; Np = 1, params, rinit, rprocess, logmeasure, args...)\n\npfilter runs a basic particle filter. At least the rinit, rprocess, and logdmeasure basic components are needed. args... can be used to modify or unset additional fields.\n\n\n\n\n\npfilter(object; Np = object.Np, args...)\n\nRunning pfilter on a PfilterdPompObject re-runs the particle filter. One can adjust the parameters, number of particles (Np), or pomp model components.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pfilter"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit","page":"Home","text":"rinit(object; t0=timezero(object), params=coef(object), nsim=1)\n\nrinit is the workhorse for the simulator of the initial-state distribution.\n\nArguments\n\nobject: the PompObject\nparams: a NamedTuple of parameters or vector of NamedTuples\nt0: the time at which rinit is to be simulated. This should be a single scalar.\nnsim: the number of simulations desired.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit!","page":"Home","text":"rinit!(object, x0; t0=timezero(object), params = coef(object))\n\nrinit! is the in-place version of the rinit workhorse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit!"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess","page":"Home","text":"rprocess(object; x0, t0 = timezero(object), times=times(object), params = coef(object))\n\nrprocess is the workhorse for the simulator of the process\n\nIf there is no user-supplied rprocess component, the dynamics are trivial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess!","page":"Home","text":"rprocess!(object, x; x0 = init_state(object), t0 = timezero(object), times=times(object), params = coef(object))\n\nrprocess! is the in-place version of the rprocess workhorse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess!"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rmeasure","page":"Home","text":"rmeasure(object; x, times=times(object), params=coef(object))\n\nrmeasure is the workhorse for the simulator of the measurement distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rmeasure"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure","page":"Home","text":"logdmeasure(object; times=times(object), y=obs(object),\n            x=states(object), params=coef(object))\n\nlogdmeasure is the workhorse for the evaluator of the log measurement density.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure!","page":"Home","text":"logdmeasure!(object, ell; times=times(object), y=obs(object), x=states(object), params=coef(object))\n\nlogdmeasure! is the in-place version of the logdmeasure workhorse. If no logdmeasure component has been specified, this returns 0 for all inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure!"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior","page":"Home","text":"logdprior(object; params=coef(object))\n\nlogdprior is the workhorse for the evaluator of the log prior density. If no prior is specified, the logdprior returns 0 for all inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior!","page":"Home","text":"logdprior!(object, ell; params=coef(object))\n\nlogdprior! is the in-place version of the logdprior workhorse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior!"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprior","page":"Home","text":"rprior(object; params=coef(object), nsim = 1)\n\nrprior is the workhorse for the simulator of the prior distribution. If nsim > 1, then a matrix is returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprior"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.coef","page":"Home","text":"coef(object,names...)\n\ncoef extracts the parameters stored in an AbstractPompObject or array thereof.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.coef"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.obs","page":"Home","text":"obs(object)\n\nobs extracts the vector of observables from a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.obs"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.states","page":"Home","text":"states(object)\n\nstates extracts the latent state trajectory of a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.states"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.init_state","page":"Home","text":"init_state(object)\n\ninit_state extracts the latent state at time t0.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.init_state"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.times","page":"Home","text":"times(object)\n\ntimes extracts the time vector from a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.times"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.timezero","page":"Home","text":"timezero(object)\n\ntimezero extracts the zero-time (t0) from a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.timezero"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt","page":"Home","text":"melt(x::AbstractArray, names::Symbol...)\n\nConvert an array into a data frame, using the variables named in names as identifiers.  If x is an array of NamedTuples, the tuples will be arranged into columns of the resulting data frame.\n\n\n\n\n\nmelt(x::AbstractPompObject; id...)\n\nConvert an AbstractPompObject to a data frame, with columns for time, observables, and latent states, if present.\n\n\n\n\n\nmelt(x::PfilterdPompObject; id...)\n\nConvert a PfilterdPompObject to a data frame, with columns for time, observables, and latent states, if present, as well as effective sample size and conditional log likelihood.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt"},{"category":"constant","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.parus_data-index","page":"Home","text":"parus_data\n\nParus major (Great Tit) census (all individuals), Wytham Wood, Oxfordshire. Global Population Dynamics Database dataset #10163. (NERC Centre for Population Biology, Imperial College (2010) The Global Population Dynamics Database Version 2. http://www.sw.ic.ac.uk/cpb/cpb/gpdd.html).\n\nOriginal source: McCleery, R. & Perrins, C. (1991) Effects of predation on the numbers of Great Tits, Parus major. In: Bird Population Studies, edited by Perrins, C.M., Lebreton, J.-D. & Hirons, G.J.M. Oxford. Univ. Press. pp. 129–147.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.parus_data"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.gompertz-index","page":"Home","text":"gompertz()\n\ngompertz is a PompObject containing Parus major data and a simple Gompertz population model. The population model has a single scalar state variable, X_t, which obeys\n\nX_t = X_t-1^SK^1-Svarepsilon_t\n\nwhere S = e^-rdeltat and varepsilon_t sim mathrmLogNormal(0sigma_p). The time-step is one unit: deltat=1. The data are assumed to be drawn from a log-normal distribution. In particular,\n\nmathrmpop_t sim mathrmLogNormal(logX_tsigma_m)\n\nParameters\n\nr: the growth rate\nK: the equilibrium population density\nX0: the initial population density\nσₚ: process noise s.d.\nσₘ: measurement noise s.d.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.gompertz"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.sir-index","page":"Home","text":"sir(\n    β = 0.5, γ = 0.25, N = 10000,\n    ρ = 0.3, k = 10,\n    S0 = 0.9, I0 = 0.01, R0 = 0.1,\n    δt = 0.1, t0 = 0.0,\n    times = range(start=1.0,stop=90,step=1.0)\n   )\n\nsir returns a PompObject containing simulated SIR data.\n\nParameters\n\nβ: transmission rate\nγ: recovery rate\nN: population size\nρ: reporting rate\nk: overdispersion coefficient (negative binomial size parameter)\nS0, I0, R0: relative proportions of susceptible, infected, recovered (respectively) in the population at t=t0.\nδt: Euler stepsize\nt0: zero-time\ntimes: vector of observation times\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.sir"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.rmca-index","page":"Home","text":"rmca(\n     r = 1, K = 1e4, A = 1e3,\n     b = 1e-3, c = 1, m = 0.8,\n     V = 100, σ = 0.01,\n     N0 = 3000, P0 = 4, t0 = 0.0,\n     δt = 0.01,\n     times=range(start=0,stop=500,step=0.2)\n   )\n\nParameters\n\nr: intrinsic growth rate of prey\nK: carrying capacity for prey\nA: half-saturation prey density\nc: predator foraging rate\nb: predator yield (predators born per prey item killed)\nm: predator death rate\nV: system size\nσ: measurement noise magnitude\nN0, P0: initial densities\nt0: zero-time\nδt: Euler stepsize\ntimes: vector of observation times\n\nObservables\n\nn: prey density\np: predator density\n\nState variables\n\nX = log(N)\nY = log(P)\n\nDetails\n\nrmca returns a PompObject containing simulated data from a Rosenzweig-MacArthur model implemented as an Itô diffusion. Specifically, if N and P are prey and predator densities, respectively, then dN = dG - dC - dS and dP = b dS - dM, where\n\nbeginaligned\ndG = r N dt + sqrtfrac1V r N dW_1 \ndC = fracr N^2K dt + sqrtfrac1V fracr N^2K dW_2 \ndS = fracc N P1+NA dt + sqrtfrac1V fracc N P1+NA dW_3 \ndM = m P dt + sqrtfrac1V m P dW_4 \nendaligned\n\nHere, the dW_i are increments of independent standard Wiener processes. Thus, the process noise scales demographically. Specifically, the system size, V, converts the densities N, P into numbers. It controls the relative magnitude (coefficient of variation) of the demographic process noise. Moreover, V determines a lower threshold on the population sizes, such that if ever N V  1 or P V  1, the population is taken to be extinct. Otherwise, it plays no role in the dynamics. The measurement error is assumed to scale environmentally:\n\nbeginaligned\nn sim mathrmLogNormal(logNsigma) \np sim mathrmLogNormal(logPsigma) \nendaligned\n\nNote that, in the limit Vtoinfty, the Itô diffusion becomes the ordinary differential equation\n\nbeginaligned\nfracdNdt = r N left(1-fracNKright) - fracc N P1+NA \nfracdPdt = fracb c N P1+NA - m P \nendaligned\n\nwhich is the classical Rosenzweig-MacArthur model.\n\nIn this system, the predator is inviable unless R = fracbcAm  1. Even if the predator is viable, the environment is too impoverished to support predators unless R1+fracAK. If the environment is rich enough, and if moreover Rfrac1+fracAK1-fracAK, then the nontrivial equilibrium of the system is unstable. For the default parameters, we have R = 125 and fracAK = 01, so the latter condition holds.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.rmca"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.drmca-index","page":"Home","text":"drmca(\n     r = 1, K = 1e4, A = 1e3,\n     b = 1e-3, c = 1, m = 0.8,\n     σ = 0.01,\n     N0 = 3000, P0 = 4, t0 = 0.0,\n     times = range(start=0,stop=500,step=0.2),\n     integrator = AutoTsit5(Rosenbrock23())\n   )\n\nParameters\n\nr: intrinsic growth rate of prey\nK: carrying capacity for prey\nA: half-saturation prey density\nc: predator foraging rate\nb: predator yield (predators born per prey item killed)\nm: predator death rate\nσ: measurement noise magnitude\nN0, P0: initial densities\nt0: zero-time\ntimes: vector of observation times\nintegrator: integration algorithm.\n\nObservables\n\nn: prey density\np: predator density\n\nState variables\n\nX = log(N)\nY = log(P)\n\nDetails\n\ndrmca returns a PompObject containing simulated data from a deterministic Rosenzweig-MacArthur model implemented as a vectorfield. Specifically, the model is the classical Rosenzweig-MacArthur model\n\nbeginaligned\nfracdNdt = r N left(1-fracNKright) - fracc N P1+NA \nfracdPdt = fracb c N P1+NA - m P \nendaligned\n\nIn this system, the predator is inviable unless R = fracbcAm  1. Even if the predator is viable, the environment is too impoverished to support predators unless R1+fracAK. If the environment is rich enough, and if moreover Rfrac1+fracAK1-fracAK, then the nontrivial equilibrium of the system is unstable. For the default parameters, we have R = 125 and fracAK = 01, so the latter condition holds.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.drmca"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.brownian_motion-index","page":"Home","text":"brownian_motion(;times, t0 = 0, x0, σ, τ)\n\nreturns a PompObject for a multivariate Brownian motion process with observations at times. The zero-time is t0 and the starting state at that time is x0. The intensity of the Brownian motion is given by the matrix σ. The measurement error is multivariate normal with variance τ^⊤ τ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.brownian_motion"},{"category":"type","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.AbstractPompObject","page":"Home","text":"AbstractPompObject\n\nAn AbstractPompObject must, at a minimum, have a method for pomp() defined. This should return a proper PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.AbstractPompObject"},{"category":"type","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.PompObject","page":"Home","text":"PompObject\n\nThis is the basic data structure for the package. It contains data and model components.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.PompObject"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.coef-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"coef(object,names...)\n\ncoef extracts the parameters stored in an AbstractPompObject or array thereof.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.coef"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.discrete_time-Tuple{Function}","page":"Home","text":"discrete_time(stepfun; dt = 1)\n\nThe function stepfun should advance the state by one time unit. The magnitude of the time unit is dt.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.discrete_time"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.euler-Tuple{Function}","page":"Home","text":"euler(stepfun; dt)\n\nThe function stepfun should advance the state by an arbitrary time-increment. The time-increment will be chosen so that equal-sized steps of duration at most dt are taken over any desired interval.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.euler"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.init_state-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"init_state(object)\n\ninit_state extracts the latent state at time t0.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.init_state"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure!-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{X}, Tuple{Y}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{W}, Tuple{AbstractPompObject, AbstractArray{W, 4}}} where {W<:AbstractFloat, T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, Y<:NamedTuple, X<:NamedTuple, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"logdmeasure!(object, ell; times=times(object), y=obs(object), x=states(object), params=coef(object))\n\nlogdmeasure! is the in-place version of the logdmeasure workhorse. If no logdmeasure component has been specified, this returns 0 for all inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure!"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure-Union{Tuple{AbstractPompObject}, Tuple{P}, Tuple{X}, Tuple{Y}, Tuple{T}} where {T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, Y<:NamedTuple, X<:NamedTuple, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"logdmeasure(object; times=times(object), y=obs(object),\n            x=states(object), params=coef(object))\n\nlogdmeasure is the workhorse for the evaluator of the log measurement density.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdmeasure"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior!-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{W}, Tuple{AbstractPompObject, AbstractVector{W}}} where {W<:AbstractFloat, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"logdprior!(object, ell; params=coef(object))\n\nlogdprior! is the in-place version of the logdprior workhorse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior!"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior-Union{Tuple{AbstractPompObject}, Tuple{P}} where P<:NamedTuple","page":"Home","text":"logdprior(object; params=coef(object))\n\nlogdprior is the workhorse for the evaluator of the log prior density. If no prior is specified, the logdprior returns 0 for all inputs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.logdprior"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"melt(x::AbstractPompObject; id...)\n\nConvert an AbstractPompObject to a data frame, with columns for time, observables, and latent states, if present.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt-Tuple{PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.PfilterdPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"melt(x::PfilterdPompObject; id...)\n\nConvert a PfilterdPompObject to a data frame, with columns for time, observables, and latent states, if present, as well as effective sample size and conditional log likelihood.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt-Union{Tuple{N}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{T, N}, Vararg{Symbol, N}}} where {T, N}","page":"Home","text":"melt(x::AbstractArray, names::Symbol...)\n\nConvert an array into a data frame, using the variables named in names as identifiers.  If x is an array of NamedTuples, the tuples will be arranged into columns of the resulting data frame.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.melt"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.obs-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"obs(object)\n\nobs extracts the vector of observables from a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.obs"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.onestep-Tuple{Function}","page":"Home","text":"onestep(stepfun)\n\nThe function stepfun will be called once to advance the latent-state process over an interval of arbitrary duration.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.onestep"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.paramsymbs-Tuple{Method}","page":"Home","text":"paramsymbs(object)\n\nAttempt to determine the names of parameters. Return the result as a Vector{Symbol}. If object is an AbstractPompObject without states, this function may mistakenly include state variables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.paramsymbs"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pfilter-Tuple{PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.PfilterdPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"pfilter(object; Np = object.Np, args...)\n\nRunning pfilter on a PfilterdPompObject re-runs the particle filter. One can adjust the parameters, number of particles (Np), or pomp model components.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pfilter"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pfilter-Union{Tuple{Union{Nothing, DataFrames.AbstractDataFrame, AbstractPompObject, Vector{<:NamedTuple}}}, Tuple{P}} where P<:NamedTuple","page":"Home","text":"pfilter(object; Np = 1, params, rinit, rprocess, logmeasure, args...)\n\npfilter runs a basic particle filter. At least the rinit, rprocess, and logdmeasure basic components are needed. args... can be used to modify or unset additional fields.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pfilter"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"pomp(object::AbstractPompObject; params=missing, accumvars=missing, rinit=missing, rprocess=missing, rmeasure=missing, logdmeasure=missing)\n\nThis form returns a modified version of object. Individual basic components can be modified or removed. The default is to leave them unchanged.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp-Tuple{PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.PompObject}","page":"Home","text":"Given an AbstractPompObject, object, pomp(object) returns the underlying concrete PompObject. Calling pomp(object; args...) returns a copy of object, modified according to the keyword arguments args....\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp-Union{Tuple{}, Tuple{Union{Nothing, Vector{Y}}}, Tuple{P}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{T1}, Tuple{Y}} where {Y<:NamedTuple, T1<:Union{Float64, Int64}, T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"pomp is the constructor for the PompObject class.\n\npomp(\n    data;\n    t0, times, timevar,\n    params,\n    accumvars,\n    rinit, rprocess,\n    rmeasure, logdmeasure,\n    rprior, logdprior,\n    userdata\n    )\n\nArguments\n\ndata: observations. The default constructor takes a vector of NamedTuples as data. One can also supply an AbstractDataFrame.\nt0: zero time, t₀.\ntimes: observation times. If data is supplied as a DataFrame (or AbstractDataFrame), times should be a Symbol which denotes the time variable in the DfataFrame. NB: the types of times and t0 must match, or an error will be generated.\ntimevar: optional symbol.  Name of the time variable.\nparams: parameters. A NamedTuple or vector of NamedTuples.\naccumvars: a NamedTuple of state variables to be reset (usually to zero) immediately before each simulation stage.\nrinit: simulator of the latent-state distribution at t₀. This component should be a function that takes parameters and, optionally, t0, the initial time. It should return a NamedTuple of state variables.\nrprocess: simulator of the latent-state process. This component should be a plugin (see euler, onestep, and discrete_time).\nrmeasure: simulator of the measurement process. This component should be a function that takes states, parameters, and, optionally, t, the current time. It should return a NamedTuple of observable variables.\nlogdmeasure: log pdf of the measurement process. This component should be a function that takes data, states, parameters, and, optionally, t, the current time. It should return a scalar.\nrprior: simulator of the prior distribution on parameters. This component should be a function that takes parameters and returns a NamedTuple of parameters. It should return a NamedTuple of parameters.\nlogdprior: log pdf of the prior distribution on parameters. This component should be a function that takes parameters. It should return a scalar.\nuserdata: an optional NamedTuple containing elements that will be furnished to each of the basic model components.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.pomp"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit!-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{X}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractPompObject, AbstractMatrix{X}}} where {T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, X<:NamedTuple, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"rinit!(object, x0; t0=timezero(object), params = coef(object))\n\nrinit! is the in-place version of the rinit workhorse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit!"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit-Union{Tuple{AbstractPompObject}, Tuple{P}, Tuple{T}} where {T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"rinit(object; t0=timezero(object), params=coef(object), nsim=1)\n\nrinit is the workhorse for the simulator of the initial-state distribution.\n\nArguments\n\nobject: the PompObject\nparams: a NamedTuple of parameters or vector of NamedTuples\nt0: the time at which rinit is to be simulated. This should be a single scalar.\nnsim: the number of simulations desired.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rinit"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rmeasure-Union{Tuple{AbstractPompObject}, Tuple{P}, Tuple{X}, Tuple{T}} where {T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, X<:NamedTuple, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"rmeasure(object; x, times=times(object), params=coef(object))\n\nrmeasure is the workhorse for the simulator of the measurement distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rmeasure"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprior-Union{Tuple{AbstractPompObject}, Tuple{P}} where P<:NamedTuple","page":"Home","text":"rprior(object; params=coef(object), nsim = 1)\n\nrprior is the workhorse for the simulator of the prior distribution. If nsim > 1, then a matrix is returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprior"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess!-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{X}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractPompObject, AbstractArray{X, 3}}} where {T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, X<:NamedTuple, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"rprocess!(object, x; x0 = init_state(object), t0 = timezero(object), times=times(object), params = coef(object))\n\nrprocess! is the in-place version of the rprocess workhorse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess!"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess-Union{Tuple{AbstractPompObject}, Tuple{P}, Tuple{X}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{N}} where {N, T<:Union{Float64, Int64}, X<:NamedTuple, P<:NamedTuple}","page":"Home","text":"rprocess(object; x0, t0 = timezero(object), times=times(object), params = coef(object))\n\nrprocess is the workhorse for the simulator of the process\n\nIf there is no user-supplied rprocess component, the dynamics are trivial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.rprocess"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate-Union{Tuple{}, Tuple{Union{Nothing, DataFrames.AbstractDataFrame, AbstractPompObject, Vector{<:NamedTuple}}}, Tuple{P}} where P<:NamedTuple","page":"Home","text":"simulate(object; nsim = 1, params, rinit, rprocess, rmeasure, args...)\n\nSimulate the POMP. Returns an array of PompObjects. At least the rinit, rprocess, and rmeasure basic components, are needed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate_array-Union{Tuple{}, Tuple{Union{Nothing, DataFrames.AbstractDataFrame, AbstractPompObject, Vector{<:NamedTuple}}}, Tuple{P}} where P<:NamedTuple","page":"Home","text":"simulate_array(object; nsim = 1, params, rinit, rprocess, rmeasure, args...)\n\nSimulate the POMP. At least the rinit, rprocess, and rmeasure basic components, are needed. Return an array containing the simulated sample paths.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.simulate_array"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.states-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"states(object)\n\nstates extracts the latent state trajectory of a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.states"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.times-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"times(object)\n\ntimes extracts the time vector from a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.times"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.timezero-Tuple{AbstractPompObject}","page":"Home","text":"timezero(object)\n\ntimezero extracts the zero-time (t0) from a PompObject.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.timezero"},{"category":"method","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.vectorfield-Tuple{Function, Any}","page":"Home","text":"vectorfield(vf, integration_alg; integrator_args...)\n\nThe function vf should return a vector containing the components of the vectorfield in the same order in which they are passed to vf.\n\nThe integration_alg argument specifies the integration algorithm to be used.  See OrdinaryDiffEq.jl for more on the choices.  The keyword arguments in integrate_args... are passed to the OrdinaryDiffEq.solve() function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.vectorfield"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.brownian_motion","page":"Home","text":"brownian_motion(;times, t0 = 0, x0, σ, τ)\n\nreturns a PompObject for a multivariate Brownian motion process with observations at times. The zero-time is t0 and the starting state at that time is x0. The intensity of the Brownian motion is given by the matrix σ. The measurement error is multivariate normal with variance τ^⊤ τ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.brownian_motion"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.drmca","page":"Home","text":"drmca(\n     r = 1, K = 1e4, A = 1e3,\n     b = 1e-3, c = 1, m = 0.8,\n     σ = 0.01,\n     N0 = 3000, P0 = 4, t0 = 0.0,\n     times = range(start=0,stop=500,step=0.2),\n     integrator = AutoTsit5(Rosenbrock23())\n   )\n\nParameters\n\nr: intrinsic growth rate of prey\nK: carrying capacity for prey\nA: half-saturation prey density\nc: predator foraging rate\nb: predator yield (predators born per prey item killed)\nm: predator death rate\nσ: measurement noise magnitude\nN0, P0: initial densities\nt0: zero-time\ntimes: vector of observation times\nintegrator: integration algorithm.\n\nObservables\n\nn: prey density\np: predator density\n\nState variables\n\nX = log(N)\nY = log(P)\n\nDetails\n\ndrmca returns a PompObject containing simulated data from a deterministic Rosenzweig-MacArthur model implemented as a vectorfield. Specifically, the model is the classical Rosenzweig-MacArthur model\n\nbeginaligned\nfracdNdt = r N left(1-fracNKright) - fracc N P1+NA \nfracdPdt = fracb c N P1+NA - m P \nendaligned\n\nIn this system, the predator is inviable unless R = fracbcAm  1. Even if the predator is viable, the environment is too impoverished to support predators unless R1+fracAK. If the environment is rich enough, and if moreover Rfrac1+fracAK1-fracAK, then the nontrivial equilibrium of the system is unstable. For the default parameters, we have R = 125 and fracAK = 01, so the latter condition holds.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.drmca"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.gompertz","page":"Home","text":"gompertz()\n\ngompertz is a PompObject containing Parus major data and a simple Gompertz population model. The population model has a single scalar state variable, X_t, which obeys\n\nX_t = X_t-1^SK^1-Svarepsilon_t\n\nwhere S = e^-rdeltat and varepsilon_t sim mathrmLogNormal(0sigma_p). The time-step is one unit: deltat=1. The data are assumed to be drawn from a log-normal distribution. In particular,\n\nmathrmpop_t sim mathrmLogNormal(logX_tsigma_m)\n\nParameters\n\nr: the growth rate\nK: the equilibrium population density\nX0: the initial population density\nσₚ: process noise s.d.\nσₘ: measurement noise s.d.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.gompertz"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.rmca","page":"Home","text":"rmca(\n     r = 1, K = 1e4, A = 1e3,\n     b = 1e-3, c = 1, m = 0.8,\n     V = 100, σ = 0.01,\n     N0 = 3000, P0 = 4, t0 = 0.0,\n     δt = 0.01,\n     times=range(start=0,stop=500,step=0.2)\n   )\n\nParameters\n\nr: intrinsic growth rate of prey\nK: carrying capacity for prey\nA: half-saturation prey density\nc: predator foraging rate\nb: predator yield (predators born per prey item killed)\nm: predator death rate\nV: system size\nσ: measurement noise magnitude\nN0, P0: initial densities\nt0: zero-time\nδt: Euler stepsize\ntimes: vector of observation times\n\nObservables\n\nn: prey density\np: predator density\n\nState variables\n\nX = log(N)\nY = log(P)\n\nDetails\n\nrmca returns a PompObject containing simulated data from a Rosenzweig-MacArthur model implemented as an Itô diffusion. Specifically, if N and P are prey and predator densities, respectively, then dN = dG - dC - dS and dP = b dS - dM, where\n\nbeginaligned\ndG = r N dt + sqrtfrac1V r N dW_1 \ndC = fracr N^2K dt + sqrtfrac1V fracr N^2K dW_2 \ndS = fracc N P1+NA dt + sqrtfrac1V fracc N P1+NA dW_3 \ndM = m P dt + sqrtfrac1V m P dW_4 \nendaligned\n\nHere, the dW_i are increments of independent standard Wiener processes. Thus, the process noise scales demographically. Specifically, the system size, V, converts the densities N, P into numbers. It controls the relative magnitude (coefficient of variation) of the demographic process noise. Moreover, V determines a lower threshold on the population sizes, such that if ever N V  1 or P V  1, the population is taken to be extinct. Otherwise, it plays no role in the dynamics. The measurement error is assumed to scale environmentally:\n\nbeginaligned\nn sim mathrmLogNormal(logNsigma) \np sim mathrmLogNormal(logPsigma) \nendaligned\n\nNote that, in the limit Vtoinfty, the Itô diffusion becomes the ordinary differential equation\n\nbeginaligned\nfracdNdt = r N left(1-fracNKright) - fracc N P1+NA \nfracdPdt = fracb c N P1+NA - m P \nendaligned\n\nwhich is the classical Rosenzweig-MacArthur model.\n\nIn this system, the predator is inviable unless R = fracbcAm  1. Even if the predator is viable, the environment is too impoverished to support predators unless R1+fracAK. If the environment is rich enough, and if moreover Rfrac1+fracAK1-fracAK, then the nontrivial equilibrium of the system is unstable. For the default parameters, we have R = 125 and fracAK = 01, so the latter condition holds.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.rmca"},{"category":"function","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.sir","page":"Home","text":"sir(\n    β = 0.5, γ = 0.25, N = 10000,\n    ρ = 0.3, k = 10,\n    S0 = 0.9, I0 = 0.01, R0 = 0.1,\n    δt = 0.1, t0 = 0.0,\n    times = range(start=1.0,stop=90,step=1.0)\n   )\n\nsir returns a PompObject containing simulated SIR data.\n\nParameters\n\nβ: transmission rate\nγ: recovery rate\nN: population size\nρ: reporting rate\nk: overdispersion coefficient (negative binomial size parameter)\nS0, I0, R0: relative proportions of susceptible, infected, recovered (respectively) in the population at t=t0.\nδt: Euler stepsize\nt0: zero-time\ntimes: vector of observation times\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.sir"},{"category":"constant","location":"#PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.parus_data","page":"Home","text":"parus_data\n\nParus major (Great Tit) census (all individuals), Wytham Wood, Oxfordshire. Global Population Dynamics Database dataset #10163. (NERC Centre for Population Biology, Imperial College (2010) The Global Population Dynamics Database Version 2. http://www.sw.ic.ac.uk/cpb/cpb/gpdd.html).\n\nOriginal source: McCleery, R. & Perrins, C. (1991) Effects of predation on the numbers of Great Tits, Parus major. In: Bird Population Studies, edited by Perrins, C.M., Lebreton, J.-D. & Hirons, G.J.M. Oxford. Univ. Press. pp. 129–147.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PartiallyObservedMarkovProcesses.Examples.parus_data"}]
}
